    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3722334275" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3722334275" />
    <a title="Lucy Tonks" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90494494-lucy-tonks"><img alt="Lucy Tonks" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624429702p2/90494494.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3722334275?book_show_action=true">Mar 25, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lucy Tonks" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lucy Tonks" href="/user/show/90494494-lucy-tonks">Lucy Tonks</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/90494494-lucy-tonks?shelf=need-to-buy-a-copy">need-to-buy-a-copy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/90494494-lucy-tonks?shelf=buddy-reads">buddy-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3722334275" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11008633304526599109"><i>
  <b>“She…hoped. And hope was dangerous. Hope was the most vicious evil of them all, the thing that had managed to thrive in Pandora’s box among misery, and disease, and sadness—and what could endure alongside others with such teeth if it didn’t have ghastly claws of its own?” </b>
</i><br/><br/><br/>I loved this book so much more than I was expecting. I&apos;ve seen a lot of 3 stars reviews for this book right before I read it, so I went into it fairily medium expectations, but somehow this book managed to surpass my expect</span>
  <span id="freeText11008633304526599109" style="display:none"><i>
  <b>“She…hoped. And hope was dangerous. Hope was the most vicious evil of them all, the thing that had managed to thrive in Pandora’s box among misery, and disease, and sadness—and what could endure alongside others with such teeth if it didn’t have ghastly claws of its own?” </b>
</i><br><br><br>I loved this book so much more than I was expecting. I've seen a lot of 3 stars reviews for this book right before I read it, so I went into it fairily medium expectations, but somehow this book managed to surpass my expectations completely.<br><br><br>We are in the year 1926, in Shanghai. For generations now, there has been a blood feud between the Scarlet Gang and The White Flowers. Scarlet Cai has just returned to Shanghai assuming her role as the hei of the Scarlet Gang once again. Juliette's first love, and also betrayal, is none otehr than the heir of the White Flowers, Roma Montagov. They don't really want to have anything to do with eachother. But when a contagious madness starts circulating on the streets of their city, they must do anything in their power to stop it. Even if that means working together.<br><br><br>I didn't really know anything about the original Romeo and Juliet story before reading this and I can't say I know much now either. I have never watched the movie or read the book and thw only things were some small details about it that I've read or read online. And from that, I can tell taht there are a lot of things that the author changed in here, making it quite different from the original story and you can tell that only from reading the sypnopsis. <br><br><br><i>
  <b>“These days, Juliette,” he said, low and warily, “the most dangerous people are the powerful white men who feel as if they have been slighted.”</b>
</i> <br><br><br>The historical aspects that we have in here were some of my favorurite elements in this book. From the beginning you can see that the author put a lot of thought in how she will connect the history of that time period with this retelling. There were so many things mentioned in the book that actually happened in or were happening at the time when this book is set in. <br><br><br>I loved following Juliette and Roma around. They were both really interesting characters and their backstories were so intriguing. I loved seeing the way their paths intertwined in the past and how they come together again and through out the story we are never really sure if they will work the things that happened betweeen out and understanding why they made the choices they did. <br><br><br>As much as I loved our two main characters, I was actually more invested Marshall and Benedikt's storylines. They are Roma's friends and part of The White Flowers. Marshall was actually my favourite character in this whole book and I just felt a bit more connected to him and Benedikt than I felt with Roma and Juliette. I loved seeing what their place was into this whole storyline and how they both ineracted with eachother. Some of my favourite scenes in this book were the scenes where they were present. They just brought something to the story, but I'm not sure what it is. And also I'm seeing some possible development in the friendship that they have and I'm just here for it. Please let us have this by the end of the second book, Chloe Gong. <br><br><br>In here we also meet a transgender character, Kathleen. I liked how even though this book is set in the 1920s, the author decided to add some queer characters. Out of the books that I've read set in this time period, there are very few who actually had LGBT representation. At first I was a bit confused by Kathleen's backstory, but once I re-read that section and talked with some of my friends about it, I really liked it and felt it was a nice touch on the author's part. I found Kathleen to be interesting character and I loved the dynamics between her and her sister, Rosalind. I loved how we were shown how different they are, the author putting an accent on their personalities, and everyone's actually. <br><br><br>There are a lot of different topics present in this book, but I thought it was interesting seeing Juliette struggling with her identity and culture. She was born and raised in China, but she also spent a few years in America. This is something that more people than we actually realize deal with and the author managed to include it seemlessly into the story and Juliette's character arc. <br><br><br><i>
  <b>“Memories were beastly little creatures, after all—they rose with the faintest whiff of nourishment.” </b>
</i><br><br><br>I liked the plot of this story, but there were also times when I was just bored. It takes quite a bit for us to get into the plot and once with got there, I found myself sometimes thinking taht the plot was dragging and some things were not really necessary to the overall plot. This book also combined a lot of genres together; we have fantasy elements that intertwine with historical aspects and, we of course, have a mystery at the center of it all. The author managed to combine all these elements really well, creating an excellent overall story. <br><br><br>What was that ending? Oh my god, I cannot believe this book actually ended like this. In the last few chapters I was just so in distress. I coulnd't put the book down. I needed to know how it will end. And that last sentence... I cannot believe Chloe Gong ended the book like this. Now I have to wait months for the sequel. * cries * <br><br><br>Can we talk about the fact that the author is still an undergrad? She is so young, yet so talented. She wrote such an amazing story and she is just 23 years old if I remember correctly. I feel like this is something a lot of people forget about when they really shouldn't. <br><br><br>I really liked this book and it don't think I have ever read a book quite like this. It's amazing how authors manage to put a twist on classic stories like, in here, Romeo and Juliet. And, overall, this is an amazing story that more people should pick it up. <br><br><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1617977017i/31153992._SY540_.jpg" width="" height="" alt="" class="gr-hostedUserImg"> <br>art by: <a href="https://www.instagram.com/polarts_/" rel="nofollow noopener"> polarts</a> <br><br><br>________________________<br><br>What was that ending? What happened? Omg the author really did that. Chloe Gong really did that. <br>RTC.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11008633304526599109" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


